# Documented gitleaks false-positives. Each entry is a per-commit
# fingerprint of the form `<sha>:<path>:<rule>:<line>`. The regex
# wins when a documentation example happens to look like a secret;
# we keep the example for operator-facing docs and acknowledge the
# false positive here.
#
# Doctrine D18 is preserved: every entry is a NON-SECRET (a
# documentation reference, a public spec fragment, an algorithm
# identifier). A real secret would be rotated and removed, never
# allow-listed.
#
# Format: <commit-sha>:<path>:<rule-id>:<line>
# Adding entries: paste the `Fingerprint:` line from
# `gitleaks detect -v` output, one per line.

# docs/security/post-quantum-agility.md line 123 — documents the
# expected TLS-1.3 algorithm identifier shown in `openssl s_client`
# example output; the openssl-style key-value pair tripped the
# generic-api-key rule. The string is a public algorithm
# identifier, not a secret. Fix landed at HEAD (the text is
# rephrased to not match the regex), but historical commits in
# this PR's range still carry the original — the ignore lets the
# PR's gitleaks gate pass.
2d96dba00b3ae9aeb95fefcaa2958bc8c750ed92:docs/security/post-quantum-agility.md:generic-api-key:123

# .gitleaksignore line 17 — the commit that introduced this very file
# carried the original openssl example string in its own comment. The
# fingerprint pins it; line 17 of the prior revision is the literal
# `Server Temp Key:` token that the next commit (this one) rewords.
5a57b23c3507800c9e4858eddb96fed1d5e4efe2:.gitleaksignore:generic-api-key:17
